<p style=3D"line-height:24px;color:#2A3034;margin:1em 0">The Druze communit=
y emerged in the early 11th century during the rule of the Fatimid dynasty =
in Egypt. Their faith is an esoteric and syncretic doctrine rooted in vario=
us religious and philosophical sources, including Ismailism, Platonic teach=
ings and Gnosticism. The Druze also believe in the transmigration of souls.=
 The secretive nature of the faith has contributed to the community=E2=80=
=99s isolation and entrenchment in the mountains of southern Syria, Mount L=
ebanon and the Upper Galilee.</p>
<p style=3D"line-height:24px;color:#2A3034;margin:1em 0">The Druze grew to =
believe that the conflict in Palestine was a religious dispute between Musl=
ims and Jews, and preferred to stay out of it. However, they played a modes=
t role in the latter part of the conflict that led to Israel=E2=80=99s rise=
 as a nation-state. Syrian officer Fawzi al-Qawuqji recruited 500 Druze sol=
diers into a movement meant to prevent the establishment of a Jewish state =
in Palestine. However, the Haganah, a Zionist paramilitary organization, de=
feated the group at the Battle of Ramat Yohanan during the Palestinian Civi=
l War in 1947-48. Having suffered heavy losses, the Druze decided to ally w=
ith the Haganah.</p>
<p style=3D"line-height:24px;color:#2A3034;margin:1em 0">In the early years=
 after Israel=E2=80=99s founding, Israeli official Yaakov Shimoni convinced=
 Prime Minister David Ben-Gurion to promote the idea of a =E2=80=9Cblood co=
venant=E2=80=9D between Israel and the Druze. When the Israeli military sta=
rted recruiting Druze soldiers, Shimoni said the decision was like a =E2=80=
=9Cspear=E2=80=9D with which Israel could stab Arab nationalism and exert i=
nfluence over the Druze in Syria and Lebanon.</p>
<p style=3D"line-height:24px;color:#2A3034;margin:1em 0"><strong>Disenchant=
ment With Israel</strong></p>
<p style=3D"line-height:24px;color:#2A3034;margin:1em 0">The Druze are not =
a persecuted minority, even if they are portrayed as such. They have been t=
raditionally loyal to the state in which they live. In Israel, they have se=
rved in the armed forces and participated in all of its wars =E2=80=93 desp=
ite the government=E2=80=99s confiscation of Druze agricultural lands, espe=
cially along the Lebanese border, and the imposition of military rule on Ar=
abs living in Israel, including the Druze, until 1966.</p>
<p style=3D"line-height:24px;color:#2A3034;margin:1em 0">The Druze in Leban=
on have largely adopted an Arab nationalist stance hostile toward Israel. I=
n 1979, Lebanese Druze militant Samir Kuntar led a terrorist attack claimed=
 by the Palestine Liberation Front on Nahariya beach in northern Israel. He=
 spent 29 years in prison and returned to Lebanon in a prisoner swap with H=
ezbollah in 2008. In Syria, the Druze were actively involved in all aspects=
 of public life. They also had a significant presence in the Syrian army, w=
ith two Druze commanders being appointed chief of the General Staff and two=
 others defense minister, even though the Druze constitute no more than 3 p=
ercent of the total population.</p>
<p style=3D"line-height:24px;color:#2A3034;margin:1em 0">Many Druze in Syri=
a and Lebanon are involved in the Syrian Social Nationalist Party, which ad=
vocates the unity of Greater Syria (present-day Syria, Lebanon, Jordan and =
Palestine). Syrian Druze leader Sultan Pasha al-Atrash led a rebellion agai=
nst France in 1925 and promoted the unity of the Fertile Crescent countries=
, which included Iraq and Greater Syria. Shakib Arslan, the maternal grandf=
ather of Lebanese Druze leader Walid Jumblatt, was one of the most prominen=
t advocates of Arab nationalism in the 20th century.</p>
<p style=3D"line-height:24px;color:#2A3034;margin:1em 0">After Israel annex=
ed the Golan Heights in 1981, most of its Druze residents remained loyal to=
 Syria and rejected Israeli citizenship, prompting Israel to grant them per=
manent residency instead. Many Druze were surprised by the 2018 Jewish nati=
on-state law, which dropped Arabic as an official language. Rabbi Meir Kaha=
ne, a far-right politician and the founder of the outlawed Kach party, even=
 called for the expulsion of the Druze from Israel.</p>
<p style=3D"line-height:24px;color:#2A3034;margin:1em 0">In recent years, t=
he Druze community has grown divided over serving in the Israeli army. Sinc=
e the early 1970s, the Arab Druze Initiative Committee has campaigned to ab=
olish conscription for Druze and has organized hundreds of events against m=
ilitary service. Today, the rate of conscientious objectors among Druze men=
 exceeds 60 percent. They have been emboldened by movements such as =E2=80=
=9CRefuse, Your People Protect You=E2=80=9D and =E2=80=9CWe Are Guardians o=
f the Land, Not Border Guards.=E2=80=9D</p>
<p style=3D"line-height:24px;color:#2A3034;margin:1em 0"><strong>Broader Vi=
sion</strong></p>
<p style=3D"line-height:24px;color:#2A3034;margin:1em 0">Israel sees the Dr=
uze as a small minority group, insignificant compared to the region=E2=80=
=99s other ethnic minorities like the Kurds, Turkey=E2=80=99s Alevis or Syr=
ia=E2=80=99s Alawites. But Israel=E2=80=99s strategy is to use these groups=
 to undermine the authority of other official or unofficial actors in the r=
egion and dominate the Middle East during a moment of unwavering support fr=
om the United States.</p>
<p style=3D"line-height:24px;color:#2A3034;margin:1em 0">It is thus cultiva=
ting relationships with several groups with which it has long-standing ties=
. Iraqi Kurds are one example. Relations between the Kurds and the Zionist =
movement in Palestine began in 1931, when Ben-Gurion commissioned Reuven Sh=
iloah, a Jewish political activist and founder of Mossad, to gather demogra=
phic and political data on the Middle East. After completing a three-year m=
ission in Iraq, Shiloah classified the Kurds as a non-Arab minority living =
under Arab rule and a suitable ally for the Jewish state. In the second hal=
f of the 20th century, Israel provided military and security assistance to =
the Kurds in Iraq. The U.S. invasion of Iraq and the fall of Saddam Hussein=
=E2=80=99s regime further enhanced their partnership. In the early 21st cen=
tury, Israeli-Kurdish relations developed in several important and sensitiv=
e areas, including intelligence, investment and Israel=E2=80=99s purchase o=
f oil supplies from Kirkuk, where many Iraqi Kurds reside. In northern Syri=
a, the commander of the Kurdish-led Syrian Democratic Forces, Mazloum Abdi,=
 said last March that he welcomed Israeli support in protecting Kurdish ach=
ievements.</p>
<p style=3D"line-height:24px;color:#2A3034;margin:1em 0">As for Syria=E2=80=
=99s Alawites, several leaders from the community sent a letter to Netanyah=
u pleading for protection following massacres of their people in the coasta=
l region in March. The request came after Israel announced that it would no=
t allow the new Syrian regime to harm the country=E2=80=99s Druze populatio=
n.</p>
<p style=3D"line-height:24px;color:#2A3034;margin:1em 0">Meanwhile, Syrian =
President Ahmad al-Sharaa has been working to build a new Syria. He is not =
a global jihadist, despite claims to the contrary from Israel, the Pentagon=
 and the CIA. Though he previously led the jihadist al-Nusra Front, the gro=
up=E2=80=99s focus was on the fight against the Islamic State, the Assad re=
gime and Iran=E2=80=99s domination of Syria. Al-Sharaa has repeatedly said =
his country has no desire for a military confrontation with Israel and has =
indicated his desire for peace with the Jewish state. Moreover, even before=
 Israeli airstrikes last December that decimated Syria=E2=80=99s military a=
ssets, Syria did not have the capability to initiate an attack on Israel. I=
ts army is a ragtag collection of militias with diverse identities and ideo=
logical affiliations.</p>
<p style=3D"line-height:24px;color:#2A3034;margin:1em 0">Still, Israeli off=
icials have repeatedly insisted that Israel=E2=80=99s military intervention=
s in Syria were necessary. Despite holding direct talks with Syrian diploma=
ts in Baku in July, Israel launched airstrikes on Syrian government forces =
in an attempt to break up the clashes in Sweida last month. It justified th=
e attacks under the pretext of defending the Druze from tribal assaults. Is=
rael struck not only government forces heading south but also the Ministry =
of Defense headquarters and the presidential palace in the heart of Damascu=
s. The meetings held in recent days between the Syrian foreign minister and=
 the Israeli minister of strategic affairs, under U.S. and French mediation=
, were ostensibly focused on solidifying the fragile truce but really aimed=
 at disarming the south of the country, except for the Druze militias.</p>
<p style=3D"line-height:24px;color:#2A3034;margin:1em 0">The new administra=
tion in Damascus has adopted a realist and flexible foreign policy, aiming =
to reintegrate Syria into the region, cultivate strategic relations with Tu=
rkey and forge ties with the Gulf states, which provide strategic depth tha=
t can support Syria economically and politically. Al-Sharaa has extended an=
 olive branch to Israel, but Netanyahu appears uninterested; peace would je=
opardize his ambitions for power projection. Netanyahu=E2=80=99s regional p=
olicy, including his overtures to ethnic and religious minorities, requires=
 the fragmentation of Syria, which would serve as a launchpad to penetrate =
other countries, such as Lebanon and Iraq.</p>
<p style=3D"line-height:24px;color:#2A3034;margin:1em 0">Israel knows that =
the Syrian regime has so far failed to impose its authority over the militi=
as in the country. Instead of giving it time to assert itself following Ass=
ad=E2=80=99s ouster, Netanyahu ordered the Israeli air force to immediately=
 attack Syrian air bases, knowing that Syria=E2=80=99s obsolete fighter jet=
s presented no threat to Israel. Israeli actions made the new administratio=
n in Damascus appear weak, thus encouraging separatist movements among Syri=
a=E2=80=99s ethnic and religious minorities to rebel against the nascent st=
ate. Netanyahu also knows that al-Sharaa did not order his security forces =
to attack Sweida. Netanyahu=E2=80=99s goal is to thwart Syria=E2=80=99s nat=
ional project as part of his vision, outlined in a speech delivered in Octo=
ber 2023, for a new Middle East. Israel=E2=80=99s dominance over the Syrian=
 military, left decimated by 14 years of a bloody civil war, has led the Ne=
tanyahu government to lose sight of the pitfalls of exercising wanton power=
. Especially given the international complicity and indifference, Israel ca=
n act without restraint, and Netanyahu knows it.</p>

